@ThinkingandTinkering I honestly believe that if you shaped the pieces of nickel carefully so they both heat and cool rapidly, and use something [relatively] inexpensive] to direct sunlight at all of the strategic places, [like little plastic prisms made of acrylic one can make at home] they could make a motor with a relatively high torque and relatively rapid rotation.

The faster the nickel heats the faster it becomes inert, and the faster it cools, the faster it regains magnetic sensitivity, and the faster it will spin, the better chances of using fast moving air to cool it.

I do see where one does need to have an asymmetrical ratio of magnets to nickel tabs though, otherwise it would not know which way to spin and be equally prone to spin either direction or even stand perfectly still, so timing the phases of the tabs heating and cooling would be critical to making sure it spins in only one direction and spins that way consistently. ~( 'w')/
